c"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">I/RTB I/RTS I/SAP M M/RTWS N/COF N/MNT N/PER NMGA.XX R/NME R/TX R/US R/USS </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday EXECUTIVES LEADERSHIP MANAGEMENT RETAIL MANAGEMENT WSJEXCHANGE SB126955385469309739639045841174423533920481 Downing, Ken Fargo, Linda Katz, Karen Lee, Mark Tansky, Burt SYND CODES_REVIEWED Exit Interview </DescField><DescField fid="ipcconame">Macy's </DescField><DescField fid="ipccodj">M </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Management</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Former Neiman Marcus CEO Relishes the 'Sweet Revenge' of Success; Karen Katz initially was rejected by the retailer, but she eventually got hired and worked her way up to the top</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>The first time Karen Katz applied for a job at Neiman Marcus, she was rejected. A senior at the University of Texas at Austin at the time, she was turned down by the department store's training program, so the Dallas-native went to Foley's, whose stores later were renamed as part of Macy's Inc., while earning her M.B.A. at night at the University of Houston.</Para><Para>Eventually, she joined the company as an assistant store manager, and worked her way up to chief executive during her more-than-three-decade career. "I always say success is sweet revenge," Ms. Katz opined.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Along the way, she pushed the luxury retailer into the digital age, steered it through the recession and a change in ownership from one private-equity firm to another. She added more women to the top ranks; about half of Neiman's senior executives are female.</Para><Para>Ms. Katz ranked as one of only a few dozen female CEOs in corporate America until her <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/neiman-marcus-ceo-to-step-aside-1515061800">retirement earlier this year</ELink>, though she is keeping her seat on Neiman's board. She lives in Dallas with her husband, Alan, a physicist.</Para><Para>Over lunch of poached eggs on avocado toast at the Mark Restaurant by Jean-Georges in Manhattan, the 61-year-old Ms. Katz spoke about her career and how women can make it to the top.</Para><Para>Here, edited excerpts from the interview:</Para><Para>WSJ: What advice do you have for young executives looking to climb the career ladder?</Para><Para>Ms. Katz: To work hard but also to take risks. I took jobs sometimes that people thought I was crazy to take. When Burt Tansky [Neiman's former CEO] called me and said, 'I need you to run Neiman Marcus Direct,' [the catalog business and, beginning in 1999, home to its e-commerce division]. Everybody thought I was going to the dark side. They viewed the catalog as a sleepy business and nobody in 1999 understood the power that e-commerce was going to represent.</Para><Para>WSJ: E-commerce is now 30% of Neiman's sales. How did you convince shoppers to buy $5,000 ball gowns online or luxury brands to sell that way?</Para><Para>Ms. Katz: The customer was already comfortable buying luxury goods through the catalog. The biggest challenge was convincing the vendors to come on board. I give Mark Lee a lot of credit. He was the president and CEO of Yves Saint Laurent. They were the first of the big European vendors to do it. It was a bit of a domino effect after that.</Para><Para>WSJ: What was it like being one of the few women CEOs?</Para><Para>Ms. Katz: I was the least likely person you would've bet on 25 years ago to become a CEO. I lacked confidence. I meet lots of young women who lack confidence.</Para><Para>WSJ: What can they do to overcome this?</Para><Para>Ms. Katz: One of the things I tell them is figure out what you're willing to sacrifice, because you just can't do it all. I joke about this with my husband, who has his own career. I say, 'We've been married 35 years and we've seen each other 17 years, because I travel so much.'</Para><Para>WSJ: Aside from Neiman Marcus, where do you shop?</Para><Para>Ms. Katz: I like to shop at Zara. That's probably the only other place I shop. But I'm not actually a shopper. I've got good people around me who try to help me put myself together. I have a stylist and I have great sales associates at Neiman Marcus and Bergdorf Goodman who are always giving me great advice. Ken Downing and Linda Fargo [the respective fashion directors of Neiman Marcus and Bergdorf Goodman] are always telling me, 'You should buy this.' It makes it pretty easy.</Para><Para>WSJ: What are your plans now?</Para><Para>Ms. Katz: My husband and I are moving. We bought two apartments in Dallas that we're renovating. I'm looking forward to spending time with girlfriends. I have a 94-year-old mother who I want to spend more time with. My son gave me cooking lessons for my birthday. But ultimately, I'll need to figure out what I'm going to do, because I have a lot of energy.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Suzanne Kapner </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-neiman-marcus-ceo-relishes-the-sweet-reven